 <a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/in-pictures-66440464?at_medium=RSS&at_campaign=KARANGA" target="_blank">Sinéad O'Connor's funeral, in pictures </a><br>2. Source: BBC - <a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-66436816?at_medium=RSS&at_campaign=KARANGA" target="_blank">Sinead O'Connor: Crowds gather to view funeral cortege </a><br></div></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-66460678?at_medium=RSS&at_campaign=KARANGA" target="_blank">Presidential hopeful shot dead after Ecuador rally </a></h2><div class="description"> Fernando Villavicencio's opposition to corruption and gangs formed a key part of his campaign. He was elected to the Senate in a landslide victory over President Barack Obama. He is expected to be re-elected in the next week's vote in the Senate. He faces a re-election to the House of Representatives on Tuesday.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 08:45:18 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">BBC</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-66460678?at_medium=RSS&at_campaign=KARANGA" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br><div class="similar"><span>For more reading on this topic:</span><br>1. Source: BBC - <a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-66457472?at_medium=RSS&at_campaign=KARANGA" target="_blank">Candidate in Ecuador's presidential election Fernando Villavicencio shot dead </a><br></div></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/live/2023/aug/10/hawaii-fires-wildfires-lahaina-maui-death-toll-latest-updates" target="_blank">Hawaii fires: at least 36 killed as wildfire sweeps through Maui – latest updates</a></h2><div class="description"> High wind and red flag warning alerts for Hawaii have been canceled as wind speeds are expected to decrease slightly on Thursday. Gusts of 25-35 mph (40-56 kph) are still anticipated, which could still hamper fire containment efforts, but is much lower than the last couple of days. Thousands evacuated as officials report at least 270 buildings damaged.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 12:34:50 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/live/2023/aug/10/hawaii-fires-wildfires-lahaina-maui-death-toll-latest-updates" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/10/ecuador-presidential-candidate-fernando-villavicencio-killed" target="_blank">Ecuadorian presidential candidate Fernando Villavicencio assassinated</a></h2><div class="description"> Fernando Villavicencio was shot dead as he left a campaign event in Quito, Ecuador. The former journalist was outspoken about links between organised crime and politics. The central issue in Ecuador's election is the rise in violent and organised crime. The country has seen a sharp rise in violence and crime in recent years.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 06:39:59 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/10/ecuador-presidential-candidate-fernando-villavicencio-killed" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023/aug/10/wilko-collapses-into-administration-after-rescue-talks-fail" target="_blank">Wilko collapses into administration after rescue talks fail</a></h2><div class="description"> Dozens of stores expected to close after UK budget retailer fails to find new funding. Family-owned household and garden products retailer has about 400 stores. It is expected to have to close dozens of outlets, leaving gaps on high streets. More than 12,000 jobs at risk after it failed to agree a rescue deal.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 10:25:03 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/business/2023/aug/10/wilko-collapses-into-administration-after-rescue-talks-fail" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/media/2023/aug/10/disney-raises-us-streaming-prices-and-plans-rise-in-uk" target="_blank">Disney raises US streaming prices and plans £3 monthly rise in UK</a></h2><div class="description"> Disney+ UK monthly charge to rise from 1 November, coinciding with launch of cheaper ad-supported tier. The monthly cost of ad-free Disney+ in the US will rise by $3 to almost $14. Hulu will go up 20% to $18.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 11:26:01 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/media/2023/aug/10/disney-raises-us-streaming-prices-and-plans-rise-in-uk" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2023/aug/10/suella-braverman-oxford-street-london-shops-arrests-social-media-tiktok" target="_blank">People in Oxford Street clashes must be ‘hunted down’, says Suella Braverman</a></h2><div class="description"> Suella Braverman calls for those who took part in a suspected raid of shops on London’s Oxford Street to be ‘hunted down’ Home secretary calls on police ‘to do whatever necessary to restore public order’ after suspected looting. Footage showed police wielding batons in clashes with dozens of young men and teenagers.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 12:08:34 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2023/aug/10/suella-braverman-oxford-street-london-shops-arrests-social-media-tiktok" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2023/aug/10/two-doors-down-creator-simon-carlyle-dies" target="_blank">Two Doors Down creator Simon Carlyle dies aged 48</a></h2><div class="description"> Simon Carlyle hailed as ‘major comedic talent’ who also worked on Changing Ends and Boy Meets Girl. His manager, Amanda Davis, said he was known for being supportive and collaborative with other creators. Two Doors Down creator hailed as 'brilliant, funny, mercurial and magnificent'</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 07:54:35 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2023/aug/10/two-doors-down-creator-simon-carlyle-dies" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2023/aug/10/grant-shapps-tories-net-zero-energy-security-uk-politics-live" target="_blank">Tory deputy chair Lee Anderson ‘very angry’ small boat arrivals numbers may have passed 100,000 – UK politics live</a></h2><div class="description"> Royal College of Nursing says NHS is ‘falling into deeper crisis’ 74% of patients in England were seen within four hours in A&Es last month, up from 73.3% in June. NHS recovery plan sets target of March 2024 for 76% of A&E patients to be seen within 4 hours.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 12:32:09 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2023/aug/10/grant-shapps-tories-net-zero-energy-security-uk-politics-live" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2023/aug/10/russia-ukraine-war-live-air-defences-shoot-down-drones-targeting-moscow-and-sevastopol-russian-officials-say" target="_blank">Russia-Ukraine war live: air defences shoot down drones targeting Moscow and Sevastopol, Russian officials say</a></h2><div class="description"> Russian army released ten ‘Shahed’ drones over Ukraine at night. Air force reported air defence managed to destroy seven. Two drones downed in Moscow area, mayor says. 11 intercepted in occupied Crimea, Russian defence ministry says. Air defence forces also worked in the Khmelnytskyi region.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 12:43:18 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2023/aug/10/russia-ukraine-war-live-air-defences-shoot-down-drones-targeting-moscow-and-sevastopol-russian-officials-say" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/aug/10/elon-musk-to-auction-off-twitter-memorabilia-from-san-francisco-hq" target="_blank">Elon Musk to auction off Twitter memorabilia from San Francisco HQ</a></h2><div class="description"> Platform rebranded X last month with a new logo, an X, replacing its distinctive bird symbol. Musk tweeted: “And soon we shall bid adieu to the Twitter brand and, gradually, all the birds” List of 584 lots includes Twitter signs, a wooden bird table and outsized bird cages.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 11:07:44 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">tech</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/aug/10/elon-musk-to-auction-off-twitter-memorabilia-from-san-francisco-hq" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/10/african-penguins-could-be-extinct-by-2035-campaigners-say" target="_blank">African penguins could be extinct by 2035, campaigners say</a></h2><div class="description"> Population has declined dramatically thanks to overfishing and environmental changes in the Pacific. In the early 20th century, there were probably several million breeding pairs. Today, fewer than 11,000 breeding pairs remain and population continues to decline sharply. Campaigners say penguins are on track for extinction by 2035 if measures are not taken.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 12:34:51 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/10/african-penguins-could-be-extinct-by-2035-campaigners-say" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/ng-interactive/2023/aug/10/how-bakhmut-became-a-pivot-in-the-ukraine-war" target="_blank">How Bakhmut became a pivot in the Ukraine war</a></h2><div class="description"> Since the beginning of 2023, a prolonged and bloody battle has been waged for control of a mid-sized Ukrainian city. Why is Bakhmut an inflection point, and who stands to gain from its capture? Continue reading: Why is the city at a pivotal moment in its history?</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 07:05:04 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/ng-interactive/2023/aug/10/how-bakhmut-became-a-pivot-in-the-ukraine-war" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/10/co-founder-of-russian-tech-giant-yandex-condemns-barbaric-war" target="_blank">Co-founder of Russian tech giant Yandex condemns ‘barbaric’ war</a></h2><div class="description"> Arkady Volozh, who lives in Israel, offers some of strongest criticism yet by a prominent Russian business figure. Yandex co-founder of Russia’s biggest internet firm, Arkady, said: “Russia's invasion of Ukraine is barbaric, and I am categorically against it”</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 12:29:01 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">tech</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/10/co-founder-of-russian-tech-giant-yandex-condemns-barbaric-war" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/09/mines-drone-strikes-organised-plan-to-export-ukraine-grain-via-danube-ports-is-no-easy-fix" target="_blank">Turning food into a weapon: how Russia resorted to one of the oldest forms of warfare</a></h2><div class="description"> With Russia blockading Ukraine’s eastern ports, an alternative route to the west is possible but faces serious problems. Moscow pulled out of an UN-brokered deal to allow Ukrainian grain exports through the Black Sea last month. The mining of the Kakhovka dam in June threatens to turn southern Ukrainian farmland into a dustbowl.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 17:47:24 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/09/mines-drone-strikes-organised-plan-to-export-ukraine-grain-via-danube-ports-is-no-easy-fix" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/10/dining-across-the-divide-grainne-marlon" target="_blank">Dining across the divide: ‘He’s definitely more eat-the-rich and I’m a bit more nibble at them’</a></h2><div class="description"> Both are republicans and agree on Boris Johnson and banning private schools. But will they see eye-to-eye on inheritance? They are both republicans, agree on everything from Boris Johnson to Boris's ban on private schools? Here's how to find out if you're going to inherit your inheritance.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 11:30:30 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/10/dining-across-the-divide-grainne-marlon" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/aug/10/20-greatest-venice-film-festival-golden-lion-winners-ranked" target="_blank">20 greatest Venice film festival Golden Lion winners – ranked!</a></h2><div class="description"> The 80th instalment of the festival on the Lido around the corner. We sort through the winners of one of cinema's most prestigious accolades. Ang Lee's espionage drama is about a patriotic theatre group in wartime Hong Kong plotting to bring down the collaborationist Chinese government.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 11:44:56 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/aug/10/20-greatest-venice-film-festival-golden-lion-winners-ranked" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/10/the-guardian-thursday-quiz-general-knowledge-topical-news-trivia-120" target="_blank">Crooked pubs, listed churches and scouting chaos – take the Thursday quiz</a></h2><div class="description"> You face 15 questions on the latest quirky news, general knowledge, and any number of obscure things that have caught the quiz master’s eye this week. Plus some jokes thrown in. How will you fare? Do let us know how you get on in the comments below.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 10:00:52 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/10/the-guardian-thursday-quiz-general-knowledge-topical-news-trivia-120" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/10/how-we-met-you-have-interesting-conversations-when-youre-half-naked-and-cold" target="_blank">How we met: ‘You have interesting conversations when you’re half-naked and cold!’</a></h2><div class="description"> Simonetta and Juliet, both 58, met during the pandemic at an outdoor swimming club. They now live in different parts of the world, but remain close friends. Simonetta enjoyed the occasional outdoor swim before she realised how beneficial it could be for her mental health. She joined the Serpentine Swimming Club in Hyde Park, close to where she lives.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 10:00:51 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/10/how-we-met-you-have-interesting-conversations-when-youre-half-naked-and-cold" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2023/aug/10/ripped-hot-and-in-your-50s-you-are-now-officially-beekeeping-age" target="_blank">Ripped, hot and in your 50s? You are now, officially, ‘beekeeping age’</a></h2><div class="description"> If a person in their 40s or 50s, looking fit, ripped, rugged, appears on TikTok, there’ll be a swarm of comments underneath saying “beekeeping age” A working definition: beekeeping age is anyone who should, on society’s cruel terms, be too old to be attractive and yet is attractive anyway.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 09:12:32 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2023/aug/10/ripped-hot-and-in-your-50s-you-are-now-officially-beekeeping-age" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2023/aug/10/empires-of-the-steppes-by-kenneth-w-harl-review-a-nomadic-route-to-civilisation" target="_blank">Empires of the Steppes by Kenneth W Harl review – a nomadic route to civilisation</a></h2><div class="description"> From Attila the Hun to Genghis Khan, a vibrant account of how roaming warlords shaped technology, religion and culture. In 512BCE, the envoy of Scythian King Idanthyrsus delivered a frog, a mouse, a bird and several arrows to Darius, the mighty king of Persia. Darius was confident the nomadic Scythians were pledging their allegiance. But his adviser understood the intended meaning. Unless the invading Persians turned into frogs and dived into the water, became mice and dug underground, or turned into birds and flew away, they would be riddled with deadly arrows.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 10:00:51 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2023/aug/10/empires-of-the-steppes-by-kenneth-w-harl-review-a-nomadic-route-to-civilisation" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/aug/10/face-down-review-ira-abduction-documentary-thomas-niedermayer" target="_blank">Face Down review – documentary traces trauma of a brutal IRA murder</a></h2><div class="description"> The kidnapping and killing of Thomas Niedermayer by the Provisional IRA is given deeply moving family context and gripping historical background. For seven years, his family had no idea whether he was dead or alive. The name of the film refers to how he was buried, in an unlovely woodland used by fly-tippers.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 12:38:54 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/aug/10/face-down-review-ira-abduction-documentary-thomas-niedermayer" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2022/sep/04/l-immensita-review-emanuele-crialese-penelope-cruz" target="_blank">L’Immensità review – desperation and secret yearning in 1970s Rome</a></h2><div class="description"> Emanuele Crialese’s film is a drama of family dysfunction and multi-generational unhappiness. L’Immensità and its characters are reaching for something: some release, some consolatory epiphany, some immense personal revelation. The gestures the film gives us along the way are intriguing.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 09:50:03 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2022/sep/04/l-immensita-review-emanuele-crialese-penelope-cruz" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/10/northern-ireland-data-breach-police-safety" target="_blank">We know the risks of policing Northern Ireland, but this data breach exposes us as never before | Andrew George</a></h2><div class="description"> Our surname and initials, as well as our place of work, were released into the public domain in a data breach that disclosed the details of 10,000 police officers and staff. The ongoing terrorist threat in Northern Ireland made the news hard to swallow. There are still some officers of different communities who do not divulge what they do for a living to protect themselves and those around them.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 07:00:47 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/10/northern-ireland-data-breach-police-safety" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/10/the-secret-to-maintaining-your-youthful-passion-i-learned-it-this-week" target="_blank">The secret to maintaining your youthful passion? I learned it this week | Adrian Chiles</a></h2><div class="description"> Three decades a rock star is some innings but Sharleen Spiteri has found a way to stay motivated. The lead singer of Texas seems to have changed hardly at all in the three decades that have passed. Adrian Chiles was in his early 20s, stuck at home with a broken leg.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 10:00:52 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/10/the-secret-to-maintaining-your-youthful-passion-i-learned-it-this-week" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/10/private-jets-are-awful-for-the-climate-its-time-to-tax-the-rich-who-fly-in-them" target="_blank">Private jets are awful for the climate. It’s time to tax the rich who fly in them | Edward J Markey</a></h2><div class="description"> Private flights pollute up to 14 times more than commercial ones – yet are taxed less. Let’s change that. Tax-dodging ultra-wealthy need to stop fueling the problem and start supporting first-class solutions. Edward J Markey is a US senator from Massachusetts.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 10:02:51 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/10/private-jets-are-awful-for-the-climate-its-time-to-tax-the-rich-who-fly-in-them" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/aug/10/jamie-reid-sex-pistols-artwork-punk" target="_blank">Jamie Reid’s Sex Pistols artwork was a glorious assault on authority | Jonathan Jones</a></h2><div class="description"> Artist Jamie Reid had a premonition of punk years before it hit. His 1972 painting Monster on a Nice Roof foretells the monster that was punk. The late artist gave punk its sharp edges and revolutionary force – and by attacking Putin, carried it into the present.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 11:27:40 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/aug/10/jamie-reid-sex-pistols-artwork-punk" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/10/tory-voters-net-zero-environmental-action" target="_blank">The truth is Tory voters are onboard for net zero. What’s really worrying them is how we get there | Sam Hall</a></h2><div class="description"> The case for environmental action is clear, but there are fears about personal freedom and who will bear the financial burden. Conservatives want to protect our planet, but that doesn’t mean they’ll agree on every policy campaigners propose. The public wants the debate to focus on how, not if, we reach carbon neutrality.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 10:00:51 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/10/tory-voters-net-zero-environmental-action" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/10/black-rappers-aligning-right-conservative-ice-cube" target="_blank">Why are Black rappers aligning themselves with the right? | Tayo Bero</a></h2><div class="description"> Ice Cube has joined a long list of rappers who have cuddled up with rightwing pundits and politicians. Tucker Carlson interviewed rapper Ice Cube on his platform on Tucker Carlson's Twitter feed. The rapper joins a long-list of rappers cuddling up with conservative pundits.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 10:09:51 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/10/black-rappers-aligning-right-conservative-ice-cube" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/10/florida-wants-to-let-a-rightwing-group-teach-history-to-children-this-is-appalling" target="_blank">Florida wants to let a rightwing group teach history to children. This is appalling | Nancy Jo Sales</a></h2><div class="description"> PragerU Kids was recently described by Time magazine as ‘a resource for schools’ But it is only a ‘resource’ because the state of Florida has deemed it so. It is not an actual university. It has no accreditation. It is a conservative media company whose goal since its founding in 2009 has been to spread rightwing ideology.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 10:05:51 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/10/florida-wants-to-let-a-rightwing-group-teach-history-to-children-this-is-appalling" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/10/fake-meat-sales-nutrition-environment" target="_blank">I was a champion of fake meat: but I’m not surprised people are losing their taste for it | Aine Carlin</a></h2><div class="description"> Once championed as a way to fight the climate emergency, protein alternatives are struggling. Beyond Meat reported net revenue losses of nearly 31% in the second quarter of this year. Sales are falling due to nutritional and environmental concerns – but also because it just doesn't taste that good.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 09:00:50 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/10/fake-meat-sales-nutrition-environment" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/the-guardian-view-on-the-electoral-commission-hack-democracy-needs-stronger-safeguards" target="_blank">The Guardian view on the electoral commission hack: democracy needs stronger safeguards | Editorial</a></h2><div class="description"> A culture of complacency around data security and a government obsessed with partisan games have put electoral regulation at risk. The security breach was only discovered last October and made public this week. The perpetrators have been identified as “hostile actors” which could be a criminal gang, a foreign state, or the former acting on behalf of the latter.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 17:34:09 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/the-guardian-view-on-the-electoral-commission-hack-democracy-needs-stronger-safeguards" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/the-guardian-view-on-the-amazon-summit-rich-nations-must-now-step-up" target="_blank">The Guardian view on the Amazon summit: rich nations must now step up</a></h2><div class="description"> Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva defeated Jair Bolsonaro by a margin of 1.8% in last October's election. The Amazon rainforest was hurtling towards a tipping point after which it would no longer function as a climate stabiliser. Deforestation dropped by 42% during Lula’s first seven months in office, and the state has returned as a protective state.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 17:34:03 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/the-guardian-view-on-the-amazon-summit-rich-nations-must-now-step-up" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2023/aug/09/lee-anderson-ugly-words-shame-britain" target="_blank">Lee Anderson’s ugly words shame Britain | Letters</a></h2><div class="description"> Alexandra Wright joined a march of silence from the library in Ladbroke Grove to Grenfell Tower. The Tory deputy chair used demeaning and disgusting language in his remarks about asylum seekers, she says. Plus letters from Kevin Potter and Will King, from Will King and Alexandra Wright.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 17:28:54 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2023/aug/09/lee-anderson-ugly-words-shame-britain" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/aug/09/views-from-both-sides-of-the-digital-divide" target="_blank">Views from both sides of the digital divide | Letters</a></h2><div class="description"> Josephine Culhane was nodding vigorously in agreement when she read your editorial. An hour later she was having a conversation with your subscription team about the fact that I could no longer have my subscription vouchers for the Guardian. I now need to use a barcode that would be scanned by my newsagent – in our only village shop. They do not have a scanner.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 17:28:49 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2023/aug/09/views-from-both-sides-of-the-digital-divide" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/10/hinata-miyazawa-womens-world-cup-japan" target="_blank">Hinata Miyazawa: how Japan’s unlikely star took World Cup by storm</a></h2><div class="description"> 23-year-old Hinata Miyazawa has been the star of Japan's World Cup team. Her older brother introduced her to the game at the age of three. She stayed in Japan to focus on her education alongside playing football. Her story began in a small coastal town, an hour’s drive south of Tokyo.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 09:49:18 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/10/hinata-miyazawa-womens-world-cup-japan" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/10/keep-watching-lionesses-premier-league-beth-england-womens-women-cup" target="_blank">Keep watching Lionesses despite start of Premier League, says Beth England</a></h2><div class="description"> England hopeful fans will still watch the Lionesses despite the return of the Premier League overlapping with the business end of the World Cup. Tottenham forward wants fans to keep coming back to watch England. Arsenal's game against Nottingham Forest kicks off an hour into England’s quarter-final with Colombia on Saturday.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 11:32:59 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/10/keep-watching-lionesses-premier-league-beth-england-womens-women-cup" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/10/they-have-a-really-big-mouth-dutch-forward-delights-in-us-world-cup-exit" target="_blank">‘They have a really big mouth’: Dutch forward delights in US World Cup exit</a></h2><div class="description"> Lineth Beerensteyn says US were ‘already talking about the final’ The Dutch drew 1-1 with the US to finish ahead of them in Group E. The Americans were then eliminated by Sweden in the last 16, the first time in history they had gone out before the tournament semi-finals.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 09:22:50 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/10/they-have-a-really-big-mouth-dutch-forward-delights-in-us-world-cup-exit" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/09/womens-world-cup-2023-last-16-power-rankings-england-france-australia-usa" target="_blank">Women’s World Cup power rankings: France on the rise, England drop down</a></h2><div class="description"> Japan continue to look the most in-form team in the competition. France, Australia, Spain and Colombia are all making upward moves. Hinata Miyazawa remains top scorer with five goals, equalling Homare Sawa’s Golden Boot-winning total in 2011.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 12:19:45 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/09/womens-world-cup-2023-last-16-power-rankings-england-france-australia-usa" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/10/tottenham-accept-harry-kane-offer-bayern-munich" target="_blank">Tottenham accept Harry Kane offer from Bayern Munich</a></h2><div class="description"> Tottenham have accepted an offer from Bayern Munich for Harry Kane. German champions had several bids rejected before reaching an agreement. Spurs rejected several bids before striking deal with Bayern Munich. Bayern confident Kane will agree terms and join the Premier League giants. Kane keen for future to be resolved before Tottenham’s first game on Sunday against Brentford.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 09:59:59 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/10/tottenham-accept-harry-kane-offer-bayern-munich" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/ng-interactive/2023/aug/10/david-squires-on-what-to-expect-in-the-premier-league-this-season" target="_blank">David Squires on … what to expect in the Premier League this season</a></h2><div class="description"> David is our resident cartoonist on the forthcoming campaign, featuring Ralph from Happy Days, a dancing Roy and Proper Football Men. You can get a copy of his cartoons in the Guardian Print Store in the Print Store. The campaign will be launched in the spring of 2015.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</